The place is usually quite pack for Dim Sum and the line is usually long, and the wait time is about half hour or so minimum.  If you are not in the mood to wait for a table, best bet is before 10 am.  The Dim Sum is on par with Hong Kong's.   The variety is plentiful and the food is fresh.  The taste is what gets  the folks to keep coming back.  The wait staff is normally  too busy to be real friendly and attentive,  but they do try to be polite.  The decor is nice and comfortable with floor to ceiling windows which allows  lots of sunshine to shine in.  The restaurant have extremely high ceilings which brightens up the place.  The place is clean and well kept.  Enjoy Park Asia.  Happy NYC Autumn 19.  The NYC MTA 8th Street Subway Station is still being renovated, and the station is a mess.

I have come here for breakfast (dimsum) and dinner before, both of which is mediocre at best. Once upon a time, before their renovation, I was able to soundly say their food quality is good, one of the best in 8 avenue, but, sadly, it seems their chefs couldn't wait for the renovation to finish and left to find other jobs. Most of the food here is subpar compared to the other restaurants in 8 avenue. The chicken tends to be overdone/not fresh, the fried rice we had for dinner once actually like little pebbles because the rice underdone, the dimsum simply isn't memorable enough for me to want to ever come back here for it, etc. The service is fine here, to be honest, but nothing to write home about.  The price isn't particularly cheap either to have such mediocre food (compared to City Cafe on 56th). For most things done in better quality, go to Lucky Eight or East Harbor -- their food is better and their service tends to be better. They aren't as grand or shiny as Park Asia post-renovation, but when I'm at a Chinese banquet restaurant, all I care about is the food.

Went there on Christmas day with my wife for lunch.  The wait was very long and we expected this given the holiday.  We had to check frequently for our number as the announcements were in Chinese but again this is an authentic restaurant and we had expected this would be the case.  The 2 of us were seated at a larger table of 8 with 2 other families.  Luckily they helped us understand some of the dishes which helped us get more of the experience of authentic Dim Sum.  The food is wheeled around on carts that keeps them warm. There is a menu if you want to order larger dishes and the variety is excellent.  The assortment of the Dim Sum is large and should meet the requirements of any palate.  The  noodles were very tender.  The beef had a great flavor.  All the Dim Sum stuffings were excellent and cooked correct.  The Shumai with shrimp had just the perfect steaming of them so they are cooked but tender.  There is also a soup cart that goes around with a variety.  The desserts were again Dim Sum style with the buns being perfectly steamed and the filling cooked right.  The sesame bums were excellent with red bean paste.  They kept refilling our tea which was nice.  The costs of the Dim Sum are average with some of the specials being more.  Overall it was a good experience and would recommend to go back to again.  Would be nice to be at our own table to enjoy it more.

I don't know if I've ever been so badly shamed in front of my family's friend. We had a reservation in a room, and I did not expect a room right away, as I know that the time for yum cha started way earlier than 11AM. I saw the door was closed, and I go to open it a little bit to see if there was a party in there- no harm meant. I saw a table inside and closed the door right away, apologizing. My party then went outside by the hall to wait a bit, and a manager who walked by decided to scold me and saying something along the lines of: "You should've came at 11:15! (My reservation was at 11AM) The people inside the room would have been done eating, and paid their bill!" What do you mean I should've came at 11:15? Isn't that rude to say to your next customers? The best thing you could've said to me was likely to wait for a little bit for the last party to be done, and I would've been completely fine with it. I have NEVER seen such HORRIBLE service from the managers.  The rest of the staff was fine (just managerial position with some HEAVY attitude issues), and the man setting up the table for us in the room later would chat with us, and was extremely nice in setting up the T.V. (as it was the World Cup airing that day.)  The food was also great; but the options aren't too wide. I don't think I left very full, and had to grab Nathan's shortly after. That being said, don't let it discourage you from trying this place in the area; avoid the managers and just do you- interact with the normal restaurant staffs and aunties pushing the carts; they're very nice people. Just managers with heavy, heavy attitudes is all that you'll have to be careful of.
